item.title: A WordPress theme built for tennis won't run your entire business. But here's what it will do.
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
The great thing about WordPress …

… is the way it puts your public-facing site in your hands.
  • You can get it online in short order, without waiting for a developer to fit you into their calendar.
  • You can tweak it to look inviting - and carry your branding.
  • And you can keep it updated, without waiting for a developer to fit you into their calendar.
Using a WordPress theme specifically for your tennis niche can help you do a lot of things better and faster:

Bring ’em in.

How do new folks in the area find somewhere to play? They look online. And pick the place that has the best-looking website. (Seriously. They do - at least until they have some other information.) Meaning, for their priorities. Not necessarily the one that looks the most elegant. Maybe the one that looks:
  • The homiest.
  • Like a fun place to hang out.
  • That makes them feel part of the action already.
  • That's a great place for the kids.
  • Or, perhaps, indeed, the most elegant. With a five-star chef in the kitchen.

Then bring ’em back.

We buy things based on other people's experience: preferably, our friends, but we also trust the reviews of people who use things the way we do. We love to see pictures from the stuff we're involved in. To relive our favorite memories. And get a feel for what else is going on. Plus, when things change at the last minute, you'll be glad you did the work (and yes - it is hard work) to build an email list and a Twitter following so you can get the word out fast.
  • Snow day?
  • Extra spaces in a clinic?
  • Shop specials?
Bang out a quick note. Post it to your site, and let WordPress send the emails and tweets. Automagically.

Cash flow. Cash flow. Cash flow.

If you routinely bill for it, you can sell it online. And - critically - collect in advance. For everything from private lessons and clinic spots to equipment service contracts and down payments for court construction. Concerned about taking plastic? It's a lot cheaper and easier than it was just a few years ago, thanks to a new breed of services that also take on all the risks.

Resource management.

There's a hidden advantage to having people sign up for things and pay in advance: they tend to show up. So you can plan accordingly.

And resource multiplication.

A client once put it this way: "I have the greatest pros in the country. But I only have them for 37 hours a week." Online, there are a number of ways to package and promote your best instruction, whether it's to raise your profile or multiply the resources beyond the limits of their time and energy. That too takes work. But when you're ready to go live, a tennis-focused WordPress theme can help. Check out our themes here.

But again, let's be clear. A WordPress theme is not a cure-all.

Because WordPress or not, tennis theme or not, your public-facing website can't do everything. It can't run your back office the way something like TennisSource can. It won't replace your personal relationships. (But, yes. It can make them stronger.) And it won't do the very painstaking job of building the right programs and choosing the right products for your folks. Those things easily account for 60% of your ongoing results. But for the things your site can help with, I highly suggest you check out our themes here.

item.title: The RacquetPress themes.
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
Do people automatically think you run a club?

Tennis people know our industry has a lot of niches, even if regular folks don't. Which is why we're planning child themes in several different broad categories. Even some for clubs! But they have a lot in common.

The Genesis Framework.

These themes are all children of the Genesis Framework, which I've been using exclusively since 2011. You'll need to grab a copy* to make these themes work. It met my needs in a number of ways and evidently a lot of other people's, too. Since then, Genesis has become the top-selling and top-rated WordPress framework. Nobody else is even close.

So. The Genesis Framework and RacquetPress child themes.

For your tennis operation, they make a pretty unbeatable team. *Yes, that's an affiliate link. When you use it to buy your copy of Genesis or any of the child themes on StudioPress.com, I get a little commission. And while you always get support from me - you'll be able to get it from my pals over there as well. And they know a ton more than I do!

item.title: The St. Louis Tennis Hall of Fame.
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
When the Hall of Fame came out to play in 2013, we gave it a new (trade) dress.

2013 was a big year for the St. Louis Tennis Hall.

It moved to Frontenac Racquet Club from its old home in Forest Park, where it had only been accessible in the summer. And after a hiatus of some years, it inducted four new members during the May Frontenac Pro Doubles Classic.

The discovery.

But as we were putting together the promotional materials for the Classic, it became clear that the Hall's existing graphic materials no longer existed. In fact, they probably never made it to electronic form. The choice: trace an old photocopy someone had found, or design a more contemporary version. The leadership of the Hall opted to see some new designs. The winner was this round version of the Arch as tennis racquet, very like the previous concept but more formal, befitting a Hall of Fame, and updated with current typography. We also launched the Hall's first site, on WordPress and Genesis.

2016: New inductees and a major upgrade.

April 2016 will see four new inductees: Terry Ward, Craig Sandvig, Ron Cobb and Patty Purcell. Look for news and pics on the site! As well, the Hall's HQ will move again – to String n Swing Tennis, a shop in Old Frontenac Square.

item.title: Frontenac Racquet Club.
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
In a tough time for tennis, one spot just keeps getting sweeter.

At least three indoor tennis clubs in the St. Louis metro area have closed since the turn of the century. It's hard to believe they weren't at least nominally profitable. But they sat on real estate so valuable it was hard to justify the use of that land for such a seemingly frivolous, low-margin purpose. Yet the land sitting under Frontenac Racquet Club is likely worth millions more. And in 2011 that club added 2½ courts.

What's made the difference?

Look for key drivers of Frontenac's success, and you'll soon see a hundred small signs of the deft hand and genial personality of general manager Terry Ward. His let-them-run-with-it management style motivates anyone with an ounce of energy, staff or not, and builds a big space for tennis pros to grow a following and build a career.

Pieces of the puzzle.

Margin-friendly pricing – with discounts offered rarely, strategically and unpredictably – have helped the club thrive. Branding, our charge since 2006, has contributed another, sizable, piece.

An evolving web presence.

Online, we've grown from a static site to a responsive, dynamic one built on WordPress and Genesis. Put another way, the pieces of Terry's puzzle, as he calls them – pricing, promotion, people, programs – come together to form a single, powerful brand that has become the dominant force in tennis across the region.

item.title: Antelope Valley Tennis.
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
A new regime gives a sleepy tennis program a chance to wake up – online and off.

The first year or so we spent in the Antelope Valley, where we′re on a temporary assignment with husband Dick′s fighter planes, you could shoot a cannon through the Antelope Valley Country Club's tennis courts after about 10 am most days. It wasn′t until the head pro, Kirk Shoemaker, assumed the helm that the courts began to show signs of life. With the lid off whatever had been keeping the courts empty, we were free to grow. In the 21st century, that starts with a site. As Kirk learns to use WordPress as a teaching and blogging tool, we′re adding features with Formidable Forms and Foo Galleries. And taking lots of pictures. Immediate priorities: an email list and getting more members to use the tools we've built to organize their games.

item.title: I've been playing for almost 50 years. But I nearly didn't make it past the first week.
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
I was afraid of the ball

The first day of tennis camp. I was nine. And I couldn't make contact to save my life. The pro brought me to the net and very gently started tossing balls at my racquet face. I got over the fear. I learned I was hitting a shot that had a name: forehand volley. By the end of that week, I could hit a forehand. By the end of the next full summer, I could hit groundstrokes, volleys and lobs. It would be three more years before I got a serve in. I didn't make my high-school team. I've never been in a tournament. I have played on teams as an adult, and I love the discipline. I love the game. My tennis story isn't about trophies and glory. It's about setting small goals and reaching them. And setting some more, and reaching those.

Which is also a pretty good way to grow a business.

Especially a tennis business.

More about that, here.

item.title: "Exactly who are tennis people?"
item.dc:creator: marybaum
item.content:encoded:
“RacquetPress is just you. What’s this we foolishness?”

We are a team. You and me. Your people, your players, your pros, your partners. My partners, my background, my systems, my experience. Working together, for results we can only produce  – yup – by working together.

Let's get those pros:

  • Off the phone.
  • Out of their email.
  • And back on the court, where their time means the most to all of us.

Let's keep those courts busy:

  • The indoor courts that cost a fortune to heat, cool and maintain.
  • The clay courts, whose fabric lines have to come up and go down Every. Single. Season.
  • Even the hard courts that still carry fixed costs when it's 101 in the shade and the humidity's about 250%. Or buried under two feet of snow, ready to crack as if they're sitting on the New Madrid Fault.

Let’s help our juniors learn the game and love it for life:

  • To get as far as they can as competitors, for their careers and the hometown spirit that grows the game, one new player at a time
  • To keep idle hands busy, student bodies healthy and young friendships growing in well tended, properly nourished gardens.
  • To learn the techniques that will keep them having fun and playing injury-free through middle age, and delaying their dotage until they've outrun it.

Let's invent and promote new ways to help everyone get more out of their games.

  • New products and services, new tech and tools.
  • New ways to do old things, and fun ways to do tedious things.
  • More fitness, more fun, more new players picking up the game.
  • We can all play. And it's never work when we recognize that simple fact.

Let's keep our operations healthy:

  • By generating the revenue we need to keep the lights on today.
  • And the margins we need to make sure we'll still be around tomorrow.

Let's keep our members and customers coming back:

  • To play, to buy, to cheer, to laugh, to bond.
  • To our clubs, our shops, our snack bars and watering holes.
  • To our sites, our social media, our portals, our networks.
  • To our causes and charities, online and offline, that celebrate success and support the suppressed.
  • And use the power of that one gratifying first winner to show the way up—from step to step, from ball to ball.
Let's support the game we love with open hearts and hands and gracefully, gratefully accept what rewards it might offer in return. So we can keep supporting all its people as well and as long as we can.

We are tennis people, you and I.

And we can do things together, as a team, that we can only dream of apart.
